# Lecture 15 - Redux Toolkit (RTK) Crash Course

## Why Redux when we already have Context API?
Context API works fine for small apps, but in large
applications it can cause performance issues (too many
re-renders). Redux Toolkit is a more powerful and
organized way to manage state in bigger applications.

## Core Concept - Redux is a predictable state container
It's not just for React - Redux can be used with any
JavaScript application to manage state in one central,
predictable place (the Store).

## 1. The Store - configureStore
The "global locker" where the entire app's data lives.

```js
import { configureStore } from '@reduxjs/toolkit'
import todoReducer from './todoSlice'

export const store = configureStore({
  reducer: {
    todo: todoReducer
  }
})
```

## 2. Slice - createSlice
Combines the reducer logic and actions for one feature
(like a Todo list) into a single place.

```js
import { createSlice } from '@reduxjs/toolkit'

const todoSlice = createSlice({
  name: 'todo',
  initialState: { todos: [] },
  reducers: {
    addTodo: (state, action) => {
      state.todos.push(action.payload)
    },
    removeTodo: (state, action) => {
      state.todos = state.todos.filter(todo => todo.id !== action.payload)
    }
  }
})

export const { addTodo, removeTodo } = todoSlice.actions
export default todoSlice.reducer
```

- `initialState` - the starting value of this slice's data
- `reducers` - functions that describe how the state can change
- `action.payload` - the data sent along with an action
  (e.g. the new todo object, or the id to remove)

## 3. useDispatch - sending an action (changing data)
```js
import { useDispatch } from 'react-redux'
import { addTodo } from './todoSlice'

const dispatch = useDispatch()
dispatch(addTodo({ id: 1, text: "Buy milk" }))
```
Real life analogy: giving an order to the locker -
"add this item!"

## 4. useSelector - reading data (to display it)
```js
import { useSelector } from 'react-redux'

const todos = useSelector((state) => state.todo.todos)
```
Real life analogy: taking something out of the locker
to look at it.

## 5. Provider - connecting the whole app to the store
```jsx
import { Provider } from 'react-redux'
import { store } from './store'

<Provider store={store}>
  <App />
</Provider>
```
Wraps the entire app so any component can access the
store using useDispatch/useSelector.

## Redux DevTools
A browser extension that lets you see and debug every
state change happening in the store - very useful for
tracking down bugs.

## Redux Toolkit vs old/legacy Redux
Old Redux required a lot of "boilerplate" code (separate
action types, action creators, reducers written by hand).
Redux Toolkit (RTK) simplifies all of this with
`createSlice` and `configureStore`, making development
much smoother.

## My takeaway
Redux Toolkit organizes global state into "slices" -
each slice has its own initial state and reducer
functions. useDispatch sends actions to change state,
useSelector reads state to display it, and Provider
makes the store available to the whole app.
